Results from divide-and-conquer experiments:

**Key findings:**
- Error bits grow as ~N/2 per level — total error O(sqrt(x)), same as direct approach
- Buchstab tree: nodes/x^(2/3) ratio GROWS (1.2 → 7.1), confirming O(x^{2/3+epsilon})
- Conditional info H(pi(x)|pi(x/2)) ~ 2-3 bits — surprisingly low, but the cumulative error over N levels still grows to O(sqrt(x))
- Recursive Li approximation: error identical to direct (111 vs 113 at N=20)

**Conclusion: Divide-and-conquer gives NO advantage.** The error at each level is O(sqrt(x_level)) and accumulates to O(sqrt(x)). This is essentially the same barrier.

