    {"parentUuid":"4987badd-9828-4ad2-8fff-ac6d02ba2d01","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a0ece6695be2820a1","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XYKvUSUPhfCtp2SuAaH399","type":"tool_result","content":"<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>\n<feed xmlns:opensearch=\"http://a9.com/-/spec/opensearch/1.1/\" xmlns:arxiv=\"http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\">\n  <id>https://arxiv.org/api/GOUvzIE/7j+fua2WEw7TxjhRNhM</id>\n  <title>arXiv Query: search_query=all:circuit OR all:complexity OR all:number OR all:theoretic OR all:counting&amp;id_list=&amp;start=0&amp;max_results=15</title>\n  <updated>2026-04-04T18:37:47Z</updated>\n  <link href=\"https://arxiv.org/api/query?search_query=all:circuit+OR+(all:complexity+OR+(all:number+OR+(all:theoretic+OR+all:counting)))&amp;start=0&amp;max_results=15&amp;id_list=\" type=\"application/atom+xml\"/>\n  <opensearch:itemsPerPage>15</opensearch:itemsPerPage>\n  <opensearch:totalResults>886790</opensearch:totalResults>\n  <opensearch:startIndex>0</opensearch:startIndex>\n  <entry>\n    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2604.02330v1</id>\n    <title>ActionParty: Multi-Subject Action Binding in Generative Video Games</title>\n    <updated>2026-04-02T17:59:58Z</updated>\n    <link href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.02330v1\" rel=\"alternate\" type=\"text/html\"/>\n    <link href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.02330v1\" rel=\"related\" type=\"application/pdf\" title=\"pdf\"/>\n    <summary>Recent advances in video diffusion have enabled the development of \"world models\" capable of simulating interactive environments. However, these models are largely restricted to single-agent settings, failing to control multiple agents simultaneously in a scene. In this work, we tackle a fundamental issue of action binding in existing video diffusion models, which struggle to associate specific actions with their corresponding subjects. For this purpose, we propose ActionParty, an action controllable multi-subject world model for generative video games. It introduces subject state tokens, i.e. latent variables that persistently capture the state of each subject in the scene. By jointly modeling state tokens and video latents with a spatial biasing mechanism, we disentangle global video frame rendering from individual action-controlled subject updates. We evaluate ActionParty on the Melting Pot benchmark, demonstrating the first video world model capable of controlling up to seven players simultaneously across 46 diverse environments. Our results show significant improvements in action-following accuracy and identity consistency, while enabling robust autoregressive tracking of subjects through complex interactions.</summary>\n    <category term=\"cs.CV\" scheme=\"http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom\"/>\n    <category term=\"cs.AI\" scheme=\"http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom\"/>\n    <category term=\"cs.LG\" scheme=\"http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom\"/>\n    <published>2026-04-02T17:59:58Z</published>\n    <arxiv:comment>Project page: https://action-party.github.io/</arxiv:comment>\n    <arxiv:primary_category term=\"cs.CV\"/>\n    <author>\n      <name>Alexander Pondaven</name>\n    </author>\n    <author>\n      <name>Ziyi Wu</name>\n    </author>\n    <author>\n      <name>Igor Gilitschenski</name>\n    </author>\n    <author>\n      <name>Philip Torr</name>\n    </author>\n    <author>\n      <name>Sergey Tulyakov</name>\n    </author>\n    <author>\n      <name>Fabio Pizzati</name>\n    </author>\n    <author>\n      <name>Aliaksandr Siarohin</name>\n    </author>\n  </entry>\n  <entry>\n    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2604.02329v1</id>\n    <title>Generative World Renderer</title>\n    <updated>2026-04-02T17:59:53Z</updated>\n    <link href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.02329v1\" rel=\"alternate\" type=\"text/html\"/>\n    <link href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.02329v1\" rel=\"related\" type=\"application/pdf\" title=\"pdf\"/>\n    <summary>Scaling generative inverse and forward rendering to real-world scenarios is bottlenecked by the limited realism and temporal coherence of existing synthetic datasets. To bridge this persistent domain gap, we introduce a large-scale, dynamic dataset curated from visually complex AAA games. Using a novel dual-screen stitched capture method, we extracted 4M continuous frames (720p/30 FPS) of synchronized RGB and five G-buffer channels across diverse scenes, visual effects, and environments, including adverse weather and motion-blur variants. This dataset uniquely advances bidirectional rendering: enabling robust in-the-wild geometry and material decomposition, and facilitating high-fidelity G-buffer-guided video generation. Furthermore, to evaluate the real-world performance of inverse rendering without ground truth, we propose a novel VLM-based assessment protocol measuring semantic,
  [Bash] tail -100 /tmp/claude-0/-apps-aplikacijos-prime-research/f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f/tasks/a6deadff43c71421e.output 2>/dev/null | head -80
    {"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a6deadff43c71421e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Research task (do NOT write code, just research and report):\n\nI'm working on computing pi(x) (prime counting function) in polylog time. After 14 sessions and 430+ failed approaches, all known methods produce exponential-size circuits (2^{Theta(N)} where N = log x).\n\nI want to explore ARITHMETIC CIRCUIT COMPLEXITY as distinct from Boolean circuit complexity for pi(x).\n\nSearch for and report on:\n\n1. What is known about arithmetic circuits (over Z or Q) for number-theoretic functions like pi(x), Euler's totient sum, Mobius sum, etc.?\n\n2. The Shub-Smale tau conjecture and its implications - could it give lower bounds for pi(x)?\n\n3. Valiant's algebraic complexity theory: permanent vs determinant. The permanent of a 0/1 matrix counts perfect matchings. Could pi(x) be expressed as the permanent of some poly(N)-size matrix?\n\n4. Are there algebraic/arithmetic analogues of the \"is pi(x) in NC?\" question? E.g., \"is pi(x) computable by polynomial-size arithmetic circuits of polylog depth?\"\n\n5. VNP vs VP connection: if pi(x) could be expressed as a polynomial (it can't directly, but its generating function, or related functions), what would the algebraic complexity be?\n\n6. Strassen's work on counting functions and algebraic complexity.\n\nSearch arxiv, textbooks on algebraic complexity theory (Burgisser, Clausen, Shokrollahi \"Algebraic Complexity Theory\"; Shpilka-Yehudayoff survey), and recent papers.\n\nReport findings concisely, noting what's known vs open, and whether any of this gives a new angle for computing pi(x)."},"uuid":"121af7b0-9b10-4e4c-887c-b6301dab6cc3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:37:49.582Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
