    {"parentUuid":"ce82f61d-094c-489c-a886-3241bc5e1fc2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a6deadff43c71421e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YTPL4eJxpbi6DfjFDEDeKD","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Complexity Bounds for Prime Counting and nth Prime\n2\t\n3\t---\n4\t\n5\t## Upper Bounds: Algorithms for pi(x)\n6\t\n7\t### Combinatorial Methods\n8\t\n9\t| Algorithm | Time | Space | Year |\n10\t|-----------|------|-------|------|\n11\t| Sieve of Eratosthenes | O(x log log x) | O(x) | Ancient |\n12\t| Legendre | O(x) | O(sqrt(x)) | 1808 |\n13\t| Meissel | O(x/(log x)^3) | -- | 1870 |\n14\t| Meissel-Lehmer | O(x/(log x)^4) | O(x^{1/3}/log x) | 1959 |\n15\t| LMO (Lagarias-Miller-Odlyzko) | O(x^{2/3}/log x) | O(x^{1/3}) | 1985 |\n16\t| Deleglise-Rivat | O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) | O(x^{1/3} log^3 x) | 1996 |\n17\t| Gourdon | O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) | O(x^{2/3} log^3 x) | 2001 |\n18\t| Lucy Hedgehog DP | O(x^{3/4}) basic, O(x^{2/3}) with Fenwick | O(sqrt(x)) | 2013 |\n19\t\n20\t### Analytic Methods\n21\t\n22\t| Algorithm | Time | Space | Year |\n23\t|-----------|------|-------|------|\n24\t| Lagarias-Odlyzko | O(x^{1/2+epsilon}) | O(x^{1/4+epsilon}) | 1987 |\n25\t| Lagarias-Odlyzko (space-efficient) | O(x^{3/5+epsilon}) | O(x^epsilon) | 1987 |\n26\t\n27\t### For p(n) Specifically (Aggarwal 2025)\n28\t\n29\t| Method | Complexity |\n30\t|--------|-----------|\n31\t| Best sieve | O(n log n / log log n) |\n32\t| Binary search + combinatorial pi(x) | O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^4) |\n33\t| Binary search + analytic pi(x) | O(sqrt(n) * polylog) conditional on RH+Cramer |\n34\t\n35\t**Best proven:** O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^4) unconditionally.\n36\t\n37\t---\n38\t\n39\t## Lower Bounds\n40\t\n41\t| Bound | Applies To | Source |\n42\t|-------|-----------|--------|\n43\t| Omega(log x) | Any algorithm for pi(x) (trivial: read input) | - |\n44\t| Not in AC^0 | PRIMES decision | Allender-Saks-Shparlinski 2001 |\n45\t| Not in AC^0[p] | PRIMES decision | Allender-Saks-Shparlinski 2001 |\n46\t\n47\t**CRITICAL: No super-logarithmic unconditional lower bound exists for pi(x).**\n48\t\n49\t---\n50\t\n51\t## Complexity Class Memberships\n52\t\n53\t### PRIMES (decision: \"Is n prime?\")\n54\t\n55\t| Class | Status |\n56\t|-------|--------|\n57\t| P | YES (AKS 2002) |\n58\t| coRP | YES (Miller-Rabin) |\n59\t| RNC | YES (randomized NC) |\n60\t| NC | UNKNOWN (major open problem) |\n61\t| TC^0 | UNKNOWN |\n62\t| L (logspace) | UNKNOWN |\n63\t| P-complete | UNKNOWN (would rule out NC) |\n64\t| AC^0 | NO (proven) |\n65\t| AC^0[p] | NO (proven) |\n66\t\n67\t### pi(x) (counting function)\n68\t\n69\t| Class | Status |\n70\t|-------|--------|\n71\t| P (binary input model) | UNKNOWN -- all known algorithms exponential in log(x) |\n72\t| FP (unary model) | YES -- O(x^{2/3}) is sublinear |\n73\t| NC | UNKNOWN |\n74\t| TC^0 | UNKNOWN |\n75\t| #P-hard | NOT KNOWN (but exact pi(x) is related) |\n76\t\n77\t### p(n) (nth prime)\n78\t\n79\t| Result | Source |\n80\t|--------|--------|\n81\t| p(n) in L (logspace) | Follows from AKS: iterate and count |\n82\t| p(n) in NC^2 | Follows from L subset NC^2 |\n83\t| Circuit size for p(n) | UNKNOWN -- polylog-size circuits not ruled out |\n84\t\n85\t---\n86\t\n87\t## The Input Model Distinction\n88\t\n89\t**Binary input (n = log x bits):** All known pi(x) algorithms are EXPONENTIAL.\n90\tBest is 2^{Omega(n^{1/2})}. \"Is pi(x) in P?\" is wide open.\n91\t\n92\t**Unary input (input size = x):** pi(x) is computable in SUBLINEAR time\n93\tO(x^{2/3}). Question: how far below x can we go?\n94\t\n95\t---\n96\t\n97\t## Circuit Complexity of pi(x) (Session 12)\n98\t\n99\t### Best Known Circuits (in terms of N = log x)\n100\t\n101\t| Method | Circuit Size | Circuit Depth |\n102\t|--------|-------------|---------------|\n103\t| Lucy DP (standard) | O(2^{N/2}) | O(2^{N/2}/N) [= pi(sqrt(x))] |\n104\t| Lucy DP (parallel) | O(2^{N/2}) | O(2^{N/3}/N) [= pi(x^{1/3})] |\n105\t| Meissel-Lehmer | O(2^{2N/3}) | O(log N) [= O(log log x)] |\n106\t| Lagarias-Odlyzko | O(2^{N/2+ε}) | O(poly(N)) |\n107\t\n108\tAll are EXPONENTIAL in N. No polynomial-size circuit is known.\n109\t\n110\t### Structural Results (Session 12)\n111\t\n112\t1. **Lucy DP DAG depth = pi(sqrt(x)) exactly**: The computation has an\n113\t   unavoidable sequential chain through S(x) at every prime step.\n114\t   Depth/pi(sqrt(x)) = 1.000 for all x tested (100 to 100000).\n115\t\n116\t2. **Parallel round depth = pi(x^{1/3})**: With maximal parallelism,\n117\t   pi(x^{1/3}) sequential rounds suffice. Ratio → 1.00 as x grows.\n118\t\n119\t3. **Floor-value mapping matrices are non-commutative**: Zero commuting\n120\t   pairs in all tests. Sieve steps cannot be reordered.\n121\t\n122\t4. **Linear transformation is full-rank**: pi(x) depends on ~80% of\n123\t   the O(sqrt(x)) floor-value initial conditions with large coefficients.\n124\t\n125\t5. **pi(x) mod m has invariant conditional entropy**: H = 0.537 bits\n126\t   for all moduli m (tested 2-30). Computing pi(x) mod m is as hard\n127\t   as pi(x) itself.\n128\t\n129\t### Equivalence Result\n130\t\n131\t**\"Is pi(x) computable in polylog(x) time?\" ⟺ \"Is pi(x) in NC?\"**\n132\t\n133\tBoth require polynomial-size (poly(N)) circuits. All known approaches\n134\tproduce exponential-size (2^{Theta(N)}) circuits because they compute\n135\tO(sqrt(x)) = O(2^{N/2}) intermediate values (floor-values or zeta zeros).\n136\t\n137\t### Session 13: TC^0 Primality Test Analysis\n138\t\n139\t| Test | In TC^0? | Deterministic? | Condition |\n140\t|------|----------|---------------|-----------|\n141\t| MR(2) | YES | NO | - |\n142\t| MR(2,3,...,37) | YES | YES for n<3×10^24 | unconditional |\n143\t| MR(2,...,2ln²(n)) | YES | YES for all n | GRH |\n144\t| Strong Lucas (Selfridge) | YES | NO | - |\n145\t| BPSW (MR(2)+Strong Lucas) | YES | YES for n<2^64 | unconditional |\n146\t| BPSW | YES | YES for all n | BPSW conjecture |\n147\t| QFT (Grantham) | YES | NO (error<1/7710) | - |\n148\t| AKS | UNKNOWN | YES | unconditional |\n149\t| Wilson's | NO (needs 2^N mults) | YES | unconditional |\n150\t\n151\t**Key:** PRIMES is in NONUNIFORM TC^0 unconditionally (for any fixed N,\n152\ta finite MR base set suffices). PRIMES is in UNIFORM TC^0 conditional\n153\ton GRH or BPSW correctness.\n154\t\n155\t**Prime indicator GF(2) structure:** ANF degree = Theta(N), 50% sparsity.\n156\tIndistinguishable from random over GF(2). Confirms PRIMES not in AC^0[2].\n157\t\n158\t### What Would Be Needed\n159\t\n160\tA polylog(x) algorithm must avoid:\n161\t- Enumerating floor values {floor(x/k)} (O(sqrt(x)) values)\n162\t- Summing over zeta zeros (O(sqrt(x)) terms)\n163\t- Testing individual integers for primality (O(x) tests)\n164\t- Sieve-type inclusion-exclusion (exponential terms)\n165\t\n166\tNo mathematical framework is currently known that could achieve this.\n167\t\n168\t### Session 14: Workspace Mismatch Barrier\n169\t\n170\t**PRIMES ∈ L and pi(x) ∈ NC are INDEPENDENT questions.**\n171\t\n172\tThe natural chain PRIMES ∈ L → pi(x) ∈ #L → pi(x) ∈ NC^2 BREAKS at step 2:\n173\t- An NL machine for pi(x) would nondeterministically guess n (N bits) and\n174\t  test primality. But #L allows only O(log N) work space.\n175\t- Storing candidate n requires O(N) bits, exceeding workspace by factor N/log N.\n176\t- The NL machine cannot test primality of n when n is only available through\n177\t  nondeterministic path history (not on input tape).\n178\t- Therefore: pi(x) ∈ #SPACE(N) (exponential configurations) but NOT\n179\t  necessarily pi(x) ∈ #SPACE(log N) = #L (polynomial configurations).\n180\t\n181\t**Information barrier for GapL:** The Legendre sieve I-E formula has 2^k terms\n182\t(k = pi(sqrt(x))). The fractional parts {x/d} for 2^k squarefree d carry\n183\tO(2^k) independent bits. No matrix smaller than O(2^{k/2}) × O(2^{k/2})\n184\tcan encode this information → any floor-function-based determinant needs\n185\texponential size. A GapL algorithm MUST use a fundamentally different set\n186\tof intermediate quantities.\n187\t\n188\tSource: Session 14 analysis, novel/workspace_mismatch_barrier.md\n189\t\n190\t---\n191\t\n192\t## Related Summatory Functions\n193\t\n194\t| Function | Best Combinatorial | Best Analytic |\n195\t|----------|-------------------|--------------|\n196\t| pi(x) = sum 1_{p prime} | O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) | O(x^{1/2+eps}) |\n197\t| M(x) = sum mu(n) | O(x^{2/3}) | O(x^{1/2+eps}) |\n198\t| sum phi(n) | O(x^{2/3}) | O(x^{1/2+eps}) |\n199\t| sum d(n) | O(x^{1/3}) | O(x^{1/3}) |\n200\t\n201\tThe O(x^{2/3}) barrier appears for ALL multiplicative function sums involving\n202\tprimes or Mobius. Lower bounds for any would likely transfer to others.\n203\t\n204\t---\n205\t\n206\t## Practical Records (primecount library, 2026)\n207\t\n208\t- pi(10^25) in 330 CPU core hours (Gourdon, AMD EPYC Zen4)\n209\t- pi(10^29) computed (2022 record)\n210\t- Combinatorial is 100x faster than analytic in practice for all reachable x\n211\t- primecount v8.4 (April 2026): SIMD-accelerated Gourdon D formula with AVX512\n212\t\n213\t---\n214\t\n215\t## Key References\n216\t\n217\t- Aggarwal (2025): arXiv:2510.16285\n218\t- Lagarias-Odlyzko (1987): Analytic method\n219\t- Deleglise-Rivat (1996): Combinatorial method\n220\t- AKS (2002): PRIMES is in P\n221\t- Allender-Saks-Shparlinski (2001): PRIMES not in AC^0\n222\t- Hesse-Allender-Barrington (2002): Division in TC^0\n223\t- Guth-Maynard (2024): arXiv:2405.20552 (zero density improvement)\n224\t- Kim Walisch: github.com/kimwalisch/primecount\n225\t"}]},"uuid":"ae0d0210-a2ac-4349-b84e-e50c55a7ed02","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:37:55.470Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ce82f61d-094c-489c-a886-3241bc5e1fc2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"ae0d0210-a2ac-4349-b84e-e50c55a7ed02","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a6deadff43c71421e","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013sAnffoWzP2G6Hns1iggN5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01F6KD7gKvNW7ZuXhXcxi31V","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/status/OPEN_PROBLEMS.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4909,"cache_read_input_tokens":7809,"output_tokens":243,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4909},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjDXJSgeftF5prEYUdLU","type":"assistant","uuid":"aeee00f8-47bc-4048-8076-144b4354220e","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:37:55.720Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"aeee00f8-47bc-4048-8076-144b4354220e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a6deadff43c71421e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01F6KD7gKvNW7ZuXhXcxi31V","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Open Problems: Viable Research Directions\n2\t\n3\tLast updated: 2026-04-04 (Session 14)\n4\t\n5\tThese are the ONLY directions not yet proven closed. Everything else has been\n6\ttested (430+ approaches across 14 sessions) and confirmed to hit one of three\n7\tfailure modes: Circularity, Equivalence, or Information Loss.\n8\t\n9\t---\n10\t\n11\t## 1. Circuit Complexity of pi(x) [MOST PROMISING]\n12\t\n13\t**Question:** What is the circuit complexity of the prime-counting function?\n14\t\n15\t**What's known:**\n16\t- PRIMES (decision) is NOT in AC^0, NOT in AC^0[p] (Allender-Saks-Shparlinski 2001)\n17\t- PRIMES is in P (AKS 2002), but NOT known to be in NC, TC^0, or L\n18\t- pi(x) (counting) has NO circuit lower bounds beyond trivial Omega(log x)\n19\t- Division and iterated multiplication ARE in uniform TC^0 (Hesse-Allender-Barrington 2002)\n20\t\n21\t**Why it matters:** If pi(x) is computable by polylog-depth, poly-size circuits,\n22\tthen polylog time is possible (with parallelism). If not, it proves impossibility.\n23\tThis is genuinely unstudied territory.\n24\t\n25\t**The gap:** Omega(log x) proven lower bound vs O(x^{1/2+epsilon}) best upper bound.\n26\tThis is \"one of the least-explored gaps in complexity theory\" for a natural problem.\n27\t\n28\t**Approach:** Try to show pi(x) mod 2 requires super-constant depth, or conversely\n29\tfind a TC^0 reduction from pi(x) to known TC^0-computable functions.\n30\t\n31\t**Session 11 findings:**\n32\t- The AKS approach to PRIMES in TC^0 requires polylog-dim matrix powering in TC^0.\n33\t  But \"Threshold circuits for iterated matrix product and powering\" (RAIRO 2000)\n34\t  proves: for k>2, k×k matrix powering in TC^0 → TC^0 = NC^1 (believed false).\n35\t  **Therefore: the AKS path to PRIMES in TC^0 is BLOCKED.**\n36\t- This does NOT prove PRIMES is not in TC^0 — there may be non-AKS paths.\n37\t- Scalar powering (x^n mod m) IS in TC^0 (Allender 1999), but matrix powering is NOT.\n38\t- All direct TC^0 paths failed: Legendre (exponential terms), Lucy DP (sequential depth\n39\t  O(sqrt(x)/ln(x))), Möbius (needs factoring), partial sieve (O(x/ln(x)) error).\n40\t- pi(x) mod 2 appears as hard as pi(x); no shortcut found.\n41\t- The floor-value function {floor(x/k)} DETERMINES pi(x) (Lucy DP proves this),\n42\t  but mapping floor-values to pi(x) in constant depth is the open question.\n43\t- **Key open question shifts to:** Is there a non-AKS TC^0 primality test?\n44\t  (e.g., using only scalar operations, which ARE in TC^0)\n45\t\n46\t**Session 12 findings (circuit complexity deep-dive):**\n47\t- **Lucy DP DAG depth = pi(sqrt(x)) EXACTLY**: ratio depth/pi(sqrt(x)) = 1.000 for all\n48\t  x tested (100 to 100000). The critical path goes through S(x) at every prime step.\n49\t  The DP is fundamentally sequential for the final answer.\n50\t- **Telescoped version (Meissel-Lehmer) has depth pi(x^{1/3})**: confirmed empirically,\n51\t  ratio rounds/pi(x^{1/3}) → 1.00. This is the MINIMUM depth for sieve methods.\n52\t- **Both are exponential in N = log x**: depth O(x^{1/3}/ln x) = O(2^{N/3}/N),\n53\t  width O(x^{2/3}) = O(2^{2N/3}). Neither is polynomial in N.\n54\t- **Floor-value mapping matrices are NON-COMMUTATIVE**: 0 commuting pairs out of\n55\t  C(pi(sqrt(x)), 2) tested. Cannot reorder sieve operations.\n56\t- **Floor-value linear transformation is full-rank**: ~80% of floor values have\n57\t  nonzero coefficients, with |coefficients| >> pi(x) (massive cancellation).\n58\t  No low-rank approximation possible.\n59\t- **pi(x) mod m has INVARIANT conditional entropy**: H(Y|X) ≈ 0.537 bits regardless\n60\t  of modulus m (tested 2 through 30). This equals the entropy of the prime indicator.\n61\t  Confirms pi(x) mod m is as hard as pi(x).\n62\t- **Meissel-Lehmer as NC circuit**: depth O(log log x) = O(log N) but exponential\n63\t  width O(2^{2N/3}). NOT in NC via any known approach.\n64\t- **REFINED KEY QUESTION**: Is pi(x) in NC? This is EQUIVALENT to our target of\n65\t  O(polylog(x)) algorithms. The circuit size must go from 2^{2N/3} to poly(N).\n66\t\n67\t---\n68\t\n69\t## 2. Time-Bounded Kolmogorov Complexity of delta(n)\n70\t\n71\t**Question:** What is Kt(delta(n) | n) -- the time-bounded conditional complexity\n72\tof the prime correction term?\n73\t\n74\t**What's known:**\n75\t- Unbounded: K(p(n)|n) = O(1) trivially (program that sieves)\n76\t- delta(n) = p(n) - R^{-1}(n) has O(log n) bits of information\n77\t- Computing those b
