    {"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a36884ff17e955749","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Research task (do NOT write code, just research):\n\nI'm trying to prove LOWER BOUNDS on computing pi(x) (the prime counting function). Currently, the only unconditional lower bound is Omega(log x) (trivial: reading the input). I want to explore whether communication complexity or related frameworks can give super-logarithmic lower bounds.\n\nResearch and report on:\n\n1. **Communication complexity of prime-related functions**: What's known about the communication complexity of functions like \"is x*y prime?\", \"pi(x+y)\", \"pi(x) mod 2\", or the prime indicator function? Any results by Viola, Sherstov, or others?\n\n2. **NOF (number-on-forehead) communication complexity**: For k-party NOF protocols, can we get lower bounds on computing pi(sum of inputs)?\n\n3. **Lifting theorems**: Recent lifting theorems convert communication lower bounds to circuit lower bounds. Could a communication lower bound for a prime-related function lift to a circuit lower bound for pi(x)?\n\n4. **Monotone complexity**: pi(x) is monotone non-decreasing. Can monotone circuit complexity give us anything? Razborov's method for clique, Alon-Boppana for matching - any analogue for prime counting?\n\n5. **Extension complexity**: The extension complexity of a polytope relates to the size of linear programs representing it. If pi(x) could be modeled as an LP, extension complexity lower bounds would apply. Any work on this for counting functions?\n\n6. **Data structure lower bounds**: If pi(x) queries are modeled as a data structure problem (preprocess x, answer \"pi(x)?\"), cell-probe lower bounds might apply. Any results?\n\n7. **Algebraic degree lower bounds**: Over GF(2), the prime indicator has ANF degree Theta(N). This rules out AC^0. Can we push this further to rule out larger classes?\n\nSearch the literature thoroughly. This is a project with 430+ failed approaches to computing pi(x) in polylog time. We're trying to understand whether proving impossibility is feasible."},"uuid":"626aa186-2dc8-455d-bffc-d98d6660c22b","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:38:01.821Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"626aa186-2dc8-455d-bffc-d98d6660c22b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a36884ff17e955749","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HYQoARiVMac5yPyD4DVwn3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nI'll research each of these directions systematically. Let me start by understanding what's already documented in the project about complexity bounds and barriers."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4976,"cache_read_input_tokens":7809,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4976,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjDYCivN4NazW4NnFZUX","type":"assistant","uuid":"ee06fa15-bf87-4cfe-b023-085ec3504a25","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:38:06.696Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"ee06fa15-bf87-4cfe-b023-085ec3504a25","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a36884ff17e955749","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HYQoARiVMac5yPyD4DVwn3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RMPCddnXRa6HKHChuwVEHg","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/proven/complexity.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4976,"cache_read_input_tokens":7809,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4976,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjDYCivN4NazW4NnFZUX","type":"assistant","uuid":"5abd284a-7a35-476a-aec7-ae31a112b8dd","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:38:07.231Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"5abd284a-7a35-476a-aec7-ae31a112b8dd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a36884ff17e955749","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RMPCddnXRa6HKHChuwVEHg","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Complexity Bounds for Prime Counting and nth Prime\n2\t\n3\t---\n4\t\n5\t## Upper Bounds: Algorithms for pi(x)\n6\t\n7\t### Combinatorial Methods\n8\t\n9\t| Algorithm | Time | Space | Year |\n10\t|-----------|------|-------|------|\n11\t| Sieve of Eratosthenes | O(x log log x) | O(x) | Ancient |\n12\t| Legendre | O(x) | O(sqrt(x)) | 1808 |\n13\t| Meissel | O(x/(log x)^3) | -- | 1870 |\n14\t| Meissel-Lehmer | O(x/(log x)^4) | O(x^{1/3}/log x) | 1959 |\n15\t| LMO (Lagarias-Miller-Odlyzko) | O(x^{2/3}/log x) | O(x^{1/3}) | 1985 |\n16\t| Deleglise-Rivat | O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) | O(x^{1/3} log^3 x) | 1996 |\n17\t| Gourdon | O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) | O(x^{2/3} log^3 x) | 2001 |\n18\t| Lucy Hedgehog DP | O(x^{3/4}) basic, O(x^{2/3}) with Fenwick | O(sqrt(x)) | 2013 |\n19\t\n20\t### Analytic Methods\n21\t\n22\t| Algorithm | Time | Space | Year |\n23\t|-----------|------|-------|------|\n24\t| Lagarias-Odlyzko | O(x^{1/2+epsilon}) | O(x^{1/4+epsilon}) | 1987 |\n25\t| Lagarias-Odlyzko (space-efficient) | O(x^{3/5+epsilon}) | O(x^epsilon) | 1987 |\n26\t\n27\t### For p(n) Specifically (Aggarwal 2025)\n28\t\n29\t| Method | Complexity |\n30\t|--------|-----------|\n31\t| Best sieve | O(n log n / log log n) |\n32\t| Binary search + combinatorial pi(x) | O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^4) |\n33\t| Binary search + analytic pi(x) | O(sqrt(n) * polylog) conditional on RH+Cramer |\n34\t\n35\t**Best proven:** O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^4) unconditionally.\n36\t\n37\t---\n38\t\n39\t## Lower Bounds\n40\t\n41\t| Bound | Applies To | Source |\n42\t|-------|-----------|--------|\n43\t| Omega(log x) | Any algorithm for pi(x) (trivial: read input) | - |\n44\t| Not in AC^0 | PRIMES decision | Allender-Saks-Shparlinski 2001 |\n45\t| Not in AC^0[p] | PRIMES decision | Allender-Saks-Shparlinski 2001 |\n46\t\n47\t**CRITICAL: No super-logarithmic unconditional lower bound exists for pi(x).**\n48\t\n49\t---\n50\t\n51\t## Complexity Class Memberships\n52\t\n53\t### PRIMES (decision: \"Is n prime?\")\n54\t\n55\t| Class | Status |\n56\t|-------|--------|\n57\t| P | YES (AKS 2002) |\n58\t| coRP | YES (Miller-Rabin) |\n59\t| RNC | YES (randomized NC) |\n60\t| NC | UNKNOWN (major open problem) |\n61\t| TC^0 | UNKNOWN |\n62\t| L (logspace) | UNKNOWN |\n63\t| P-complete | UNKNOWN (would rule out NC) |\n64\t| AC^0 | NO (proven) |\n65\t| AC^0[p] | NO (proven) |\n66\t\n67\t### pi(x) (counting function)\n68\t\n69\t| Class | Status |\n70\t|-------|--------|\n71\t| P (binary input model) | UNKNOWN -- all known algorithms exponential in log(x) |\n72\t| FP (unary model) | YES -- O(x^{2/3}) is sublinear |\n73\t| NC | UNKNOWN |\n74\t| TC^0 | UNKNOWN |\n75\t| #P-hard | NOT KNOWN (but exact pi(x) is related) |\n76\t\n77\t### p(n) (nth prime)\n78\t\n79\t| Result | Source |\n80\t|--------|--------|\n81\t| p(n) in L (logspace) | Follows from AKS: iterate and count |\n82\t| p(n) in NC^2 | Follows from L subset NC^2 |\n83\t| Circuit size for p(n) | UNKNOWN -- polylog-size circuits not ruled out |\n84\t\n85\t---\n86\t\n87\t## The Input Model Distinction\n88\t\n89\t**Binary input (n = log x bits):** All known pi(x) algorithms are EXPONENTIAL.\n90\tBest is 2^{Omega(n^{1/2})}. \"Is pi(x) in P?\" is wide open.\n91\t\n92\t**Unary input (input size = x):** pi(x) is computable in SUBLINEAR time\n93\tO(x^{2/3}). Question: how far below x can we go?\n94\t\n95\t---\n96\t\n97\t## Circuit Complexity of pi(x) (Session 12)\n98\t\n99\t### Best Known Circuits (in terms of N = log x)\n100\t\n101\t| Method | Circuit Size | Circuit Depth |\n102\t|--------|-------------|---------------|\n103\t| Lucy DP (standard) | O(2^{N/2}) | O(2^{N/2}/N) [= pi(sqrt(x))] |\n104\t| Lucy DP (parallel) | O(2^{N/2}) | O(2^{N/3}/N) [= pi(x^{1/3})] |\n105\t| Meissel-Lehmer | O(2^{2N/3}) | O(log N) [= O(log log x)] |\n106\t| Lagarias-Odlyzko | O(2^{N/2+ε}) | O(poly(N)) |\n107\t\n108\tAll are EXPONENTIAL in N. No polynomial-size circuit is known.\n109\t\n110\t### Structural Results (Session 12)\n111\t\n112\t1. **Lucy DP DAG depth = pi(sqrt(x)) exactly**: The computation has an\n113\t   unavoidable sequential chain through S(x) at every prime step.\n114\t   Depth/pi(sqrt(x)) = 1.000 for all x tested (100 to 100000).\n115\t\n116\t2. **Parallel round depth = pi(x^{1/3})**: With maximal parallelism,\n117\t   pi(x^{1/3}) sequential rounds suffice. Ratio → 1.00 as x grows.\n118\t\n119\t3. **Floor-value mapping matrices are non-commutative**: Zero commuting\n120\t   pairs in all tests. Sieve steps cannot be reordered.\n121\t\n122\t4. **Linear transformation is full-rank**: pi(x) depends on ~80% of\n123\t   the O(sqrt(x)) floor-value initial conditions with large coefficients.\n124\t\n125\t5. **pi(x) mod m has invariant conditional entropy**: H = 0.537 bits\n126\t   for all moduli m (tested 2-30). Computing pi(x) mod m is as hard\n127\t   as pi(x) itself.\n128\t\n129\t### Equivalence Result\n130\t\n131\t**\"Is pi(x) computable in polylog(x) time?\" ⟺ \"Is pi(x) in NC?\"**\n132\t\n133\tBoth require polynomial-size (poly(N)) circuits. All known approaches\n134\tproduce exponential-size (2^{Theta(N)}) circuits because they compute\n135\tO(sqrt(x)) = O(2^{N/2}) intermediate values (floor-values or zeta zeros).\n136\t\n137\t### Session 13: TC^0 Primality Test Analysis\n138\t\n139\t| Test | In TC^0? | Deterministic? | Condition |\n140\t|------|----------|---------------|-----------|\n141\t| MR(2) | YES | NO | - |\n142\t| MR(2,3,...,37) | YES | YES for n<3×10^24 | unconditional |\n143\t| MR(2,...,2ln²(n)) | YES | YES for all n | GRH |\n144\t| Strong Lucas (Selfridge) | YES | NO | - |\n145\t| BPSW (MR(2)+Strong Lucas) | YES | YES for n<2^64 | unconditional |\n146\t| BPSW | YES | YES for all n | BPSW conjecture |\n147\t| QFT (Grantham) | YES | NO (error<1/7710) | - |\n148\t| AKS | UNKNOWN | YES | unconditional |\n149\t| Wilson's | NO (needs 2^N mults) | YES | unconditional |\n150\t\n151\t**Key:** PRIMES is in NONUNIFORM TC^0 unconditionally (for any fixed N,\n152\ta finite MR base set suffices). PRIMES is in UNIFORM TC^0 conditional\n153\ton GRH or BPSW correctness.\n154\t\n155\t**Prime indicator GF(2) structure:** ANF degree = Theta(N), 50% sparsity.\n156\tIndistinguishable from random over GF(2). Confirms PRIMES not in AC^0[2].\n157\t\n158\t### What Would Be Needed\n159\t\n160\tA polylog(x) algorithm must avoid:\n161\t- Enumerating floor values {floor(x/k)} (O(sqrt(x)) values)\n162\t- Summing over zeta zeros (O(sqrt(x)) terms)\n163\t- Testing individual integers for primality (O(x) tests)\n164\t- Sieve-type inclusion-exclusion (exponential terms)\n165\t\n166\tNo mathematical framework is currently known that could achieve this.\n167\t\n168\t### Session 14: Workspace Mismatch Barrier\n169\t\n170\t**PRIMES ∈ L and pi(x) ∈ NC are INDEPENDENT questions.**\n171\t\n172\tThe natural chain PRIMES ∈ L → pi(x) ∈ #L → pi(x) ∈ NC^2 BREAKS at step 2:\n173\t- An NL machine for pi(x) would nondeterministically guess n (N bits) and\n174\t  test primality. But #L allows only O(log N) work space.\n175\t- Storing candidate n requires O(N) bits, exceeding workspace by factor N/log N.\n176\t- The NL machine cannot test primality of n when n is only available through\n177\t  nondeterministic path history (not on input tape).\n178\t- Therefore: pi(x) ∈ #SPACE(N) (exponential configurations) but NOT\n179\t  necessarily pi(x) ∈ #SPACE(log N) = #L (polynomial configurations).\n180\t\n181\t**Information barrier for GapL:** The Legendre sieve I-E formula has 2^k terms\n182\t(k = pi(sqrt(x))). The fractional parts {x/d} for 2^k squarefree d carry\n183\tO(2^k) independent bits. No matrix smaller than O(2^{k/2}) × O(2^{k/2})\n184\tcan encode this information → any floor-function-based determinant needs\n185\texponential size. A GapL algorithm MUST use a fundamentally different set\n186\tof intermediate quantities.\n187\t\n188\tSource: Session 14 analysis, novel/workspace_mismatch_barrier.md\n189\t\n190\t---\n191\t\n192\t## Related Summatory Functions\n193\t\n194\t| Function | Best Combinatorial | Best Analytic |\n195\t|----------|-------------------|--------------|\n196\t| pi(x) = sum 1_{p prime} | O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) | O(x^{1/2+eps}) |\n197\t| M(x) = sum mu(n) | O(x^{2/3}) | O(x^{1/2+eps}) |\n198\t| sum phi(n) | O(x^{2/3}) | O(x^{1/2+eps}) |\n199\t| sum d(n) | O(x^{1/3}) | O(x^{1/3}) |\n200\t\n201\tThe O(x^{2/3}) barrier appears for ALL multiplicative function sums involving\n202\tprimes or Mobius. Lower bounds for any would likely transfer to others.\n203\t\n204\t---\n205\t\n206\t## Practical Records (primecount library, 2026)\n207\t\n208\t- pi(10^25) in 330 CPU core hours (Gourdon, AMD EPYC Zen4)\n209\t- pi(10^29) computed (2022 record)\n210\t- Combinatorial is 100x faster than analytic in practice for all reachable x\n211\t- primecount v8.4 (April 2026): SIMD-accelerated Gourdon D formula with AVX512\n212\t\n213\t---\n214\t\n215\t## Key References\n216\t\n217\t- Aggarwal (2025): arXiv:2510.16285\n218\t- Lagarias-Odlyzko (1987): Analytic method\n219\t- Deleglise-Rivat (1996): Combinatorial method\n220\t- AKS (2002): PRIMES is in P\n221\t- Allender-Saks-Shparlinski (2001): PRIMES not in AC^0\n222\t- Hesse-Allender-Barrington (2002): Division in TC^0\n223\t- Guth-Maynard (2024): arXiv:2405.20552 (zero density improvement)\n224\t- Kim Walisch: github.com/kimwalisch/primecount\n225\t"}]},"uuid":"a9aeac81-3e06-456f-92b1-04e6a235c6d3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:38:07.240Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5abd284a-7a35-476a-aec7-ae31a112b8dd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"a9aeac81-3e06-456f-92b1-04e6a235c6d3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a36884ff17e955749","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HYQoARiVMac5yPyD4DVwn3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XydhPAUtvZxdn4SFarqScH","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/proven/barriers.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4976,"cache_read_input_tokens":7809,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4976,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjDYCivN4NazW4NnFZUX","type":"assistant","uuid":"af430651-6ce3-470c-8cb7-42f3a8912057","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:38:07.657Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"f8730f89-3e52-4285-b6af-b645d01a4c7f","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"tranquil-yawning-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"af430651-6ce3-470c-8cb7-42f3a8912057","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"5eee6cab-1a61-49f3-8bdf-ecca43ec0a1e","agentId":"a36884ff17e955749","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XydhPAUtvZxdn4SFarqScH","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Proven Barriers to Fast Prime Computation\n2\t\n3\tThese are **mathematically proven** results, not empirical observations.\n4\t\n5\t---\n6\t\n7\t## 1. Explicit Formula Convergence (PROVEN)\n8\t\n9\t**Statement:** The Riemann explicit formula\n10\t  pi(x) = R(x) - sum_rho R(x^rho) - 1/ln(x) + (1/pi)*arctan(pi/ln(x))\n11\trequires summing over ALL nontrivial zeros rho of zeta(s) for exact pi(x).\n12\t\n13\t**Quantitative:** Truncating at T zeros gives error O(x/T). For error < 1,\n14\tneed T > x, costing O(x^{3/2}) to compute x zeros.\n15\t\n16\t**Source:** Riemann (1859), von Mangoldt (explicit formula with error terms).\n17\t\n18\t---\n19\t\n20\t## 2. GUE Statistics of Zeros (PROVEN numerically, conjectured theoretically)\n21\t\n22\t**Statement:** The local spacings of zeta zeros follow GUE (Gaussian Unitary\n23\tEnsemble) statistics. This means the zero contributions to the explicit formula\n24\thave random-looking phases.\n25\t\n26\t**Implication:** No shortcut exists for summing zeta zero contributions.\n27\tPartial sums are unpredictable from any prefix (confirmed by spectral\n28\tflatness 0.91).\n29\t\n30\t**Source:** Montgomery (1973, pair correlation conjecture), Odlyzko (1987,\n31\tnumerical verification to 10^20).\n32\t\n33\t---\n34\t\n35\t## 3. Mauduit-Rivat Theorem (PROVEN, 2010)\n36\t\n37\t**Statement:** The prime indicator function is NOT k-automatic for any k >= 2.\n38\t\n39\t**Implication:** No finite automaton can generate the sequence of primes.\n40\tRules out all finite-state approaches to prime prediction.\n41\t\n42\t**Source:** Mauduit & Rivat, \"Sur un probleme de Gelfond: la somme des\n43\tchiffres des nombres premiers,\" Annals of Mathematics 171 (2010), 1591-1646.\n44\t\n45\t---\n46\t\n47\t## 4. PRIMES Not in AC^0 (PROVEN)\n48\t\n49\t**Statement:** The primality decision problem cannot be computed by\n50\tconstant-depth unbounded fan-in Boolean circuits.\n51\t\n52\t**Extension:** Also not in AC^0[p] for any prime p.\n53\t\n54\t**Source:** Allender, Saks, Shparlinski (2001).\n55\t\n56\t---\n57\t\n58\t## 5. Aggarwal Optimality (PROVEN, 2025)\n59\t\n60\t**Statement:** Binary search on pi(x) evaluations is asymptotically optimal\n61\tamong sieve-based methods for computing p(n).\n62\t\n63\t**Quantitative:**\n64\t- Best sieve for p(n): O(n log n / log log n)\n65\t- Binary search + pi(x): O(sqrt(n) * (log n)^4)\n66\t- Binary search wins by factor ~sqrt(n)\n67\t\n68\t**Source:** Aggarwal, \"A Note on the Complexity of Computing p_n,\"\n69\tarXiv:2510.16285 (2025).\n70\t\n71\t---\n72\t\n73\t## 6. Parity Barrier (PROVEN)\n74\t\n75\t**Statement:** Linear sieve methods cannot distinguish between numbers with\n76\tan even vs odd number of prime factors. This limits sieve-based approaches\n77\tto prime counting.\n78\t\n79\t**Source:** Selberg (1950s), formalized by Bombieri (1976).\n80\t\n81\t---\n82\t\n83\t## 7. Volume-Law Entanglement of Primes (PROVEN numerically)\n84\t\n85\t**Statement:** The prime state |P_n> (superposition of primes encoded in binary)\n86\thas von Neumann entanglement entropy S ~ (7/8) * n/2. This is volume-law\n87\t(linear in system size), implying exponential MPS bond dimension.\n88\t\n89\t**Implication:** Tensor network / matrix product state methods cannot\n90\tefficiently represent the prime indicator function.\n91\t\n92\t**Source:** Latorre & Sierra, \"There is entanglement in the primes,\"\n93\tarXiv:1403.4765 (2014). Garcia-Martin et al., Quantum 4, 371 (2020).\n94\t\n95\t---\n96\t\n97\t## 8. Prime Coding Theorem (PROVEN, 2023)\n98\t\n99\t**Statement:** The expected Kolmogorov complexity of the prime indicator\n100\tsequence up to N is E[K_U(X_N)] ~ pi(N) * ln(N) ~ N bits. Machine learning\n101\tcannot discover a compressible prime formula.\n102\t\n103\t**Source:** Kolpakov & Rocke, arXiv:2308.10817 (2023).\n104\t\n105\t---\n106\t\n107\t## 9. Smooth Interpolation Barrier (PROVEN)\n108\t\n109\t**Statement:** No smooth function of finitely many analytic basis functions\n110\tcan predict exact primes. The best smooth approximation to p(n) has error\n111\tO(sqrt(p(n)) / ln(p(n))), which grows faster than prime gaps O(ln(p(n))).\n112\t\n113\t**Quantitative:** Basis-function regression (10 terms including n*ln(n),\n114\tn*ln(ln(n)), n/ln(n)^k) on 8000 training primes achieves only 8/2000\n115\texact matches on test set. Error/gap ratio is 6.5x. Even snapping to\n116\tnearest prime recovers only 4% of test primes.\n117\t\n118\t**Implication:** The exact positions of primes encode arithmetic information\n119\tthat cannot be compressed into any finite set of smooth basis functions.\n120\t\n121\t**Source in project:** session1, notes_algebraic.md, algebraic_formulas.py\n122\t\n123\t---\n124\t\n125\t## 10. Closed-Form Prime Formulas Are Circular (PROVEN)\n126\t\n127\t**Statement:** All known \"closed-form\" formulas for primes (Mills' constant,\n128\tWillans' formula, floor-sum methods) are computationally circular or worse\n129\tthan brute force.\n130\t\n131\t**Specifics:**\n132\t- **Mills' constant:** Computing A to sufficient precision requires knowing\n133\t  the primes it generates. Digits needed grow exponentially (80 digits for\n134\t  just p_5).\n135\t- **Willans' formula:** Requires computing (j-1)! for j up to 2^n. For\n136\t  p(15)=47, needs factorials up to 32768!. Slower than trial division.\n137\t- **Floor-sum method:** O(x^2) -- trial division rewritten in floor arithmetic.\n138\t\n139\t**Source in project:** session1, notes_algebraic.md\n140\t\n141\t---\n142\t\n143\t## 11. Richardson Extrapolation Improves But Does Not Eliminate the Zero-Sum Barrier (PROVEN numerically)\n144\t\n145\t**Statement:** Richardson extrapolation (alpha=1) on the Riemann explicit\n146\tformula partial sums at N=500 and N=1000 zeros gives exact pi(10^6).\n147\tThe truncation error scales as |error| ~ sqrt(x) * ln(T) / T, and\n148\tRichardson cancels the leading O(1/N) term, reducing effective error to\n149\tO(1/N^2).\n150\t\n151\t**Quantitative:**\n152\t- Plain sum at 1000 zeros: error +2.55 for pi(10^6)\n153\t- Richardson (500,1000): error +0.49 -> rounds to EXACT\n154\t- Without acceleration: need ~10,000 zeros for exact pi(10^6)\n155\t- With Richardson: 1000 zeros suffice\n156\t\n157\t**Critical negative result:** Window functions (Hanning, Gaussian, Lanczos,\n158\tCesaro) HURT for large x -- they increase error by suppressing late terms\n159\tthat partially cancel the DC bias. Shanks/Wynn epsilon algorithm also\n160\tfails (error -22 at N=300 for x=10^6).\n161\t\n162\t**Source in project:** session1, notes_convergence.md, convergence_accel.py\n163\t\n164\t---\n165\t\n166\t## 12. Convergence Acceleration Cannot Beat Zero-Sum Barrier (CONFIRMED numerically, Session 11)\n167\t\n168\t**Statement:** No linear convergence acceleration method (Richardson of any order,\n169\tLevin u/t, Weniger delta, smoothed explicit formulas) can reduce the number of\n170\tzeta zeros needed from O(sqrt(x)) to subpolynomial.\n171\t\n172\t**Quantitative:**\n173\t- Error structure is oscillatory, NOT clean 1/N expansion (alpha varies: -1.6 to 2.9)\n174\t- Levin transforms are WORSE than plain summation for large x\n175\t- Richardson order >2 diverges due to condition number explosion (10^{3k})\n176\t- Minimum zeros scale as N_min ~ C * x^alpha with alpha = 0.25--0.37 (power law)\n177\t- Smoothed formula (psi/ln x) catastrophic: 10% error from prime power terms\n178\t\n179\t**Implication:** The explicit formula truncation error encodes GUE-random phases\n180\tof the next zeta zeros beyond the truncation point. No linear combination of\n181\tpartial sums can predict these phases. The barrier is informational, not technical.\n182\t\n183\t**Source in project:** session11, experiments/analytic/advanced_convergence.py, zero_scaling.py\n184\t\n185\t---\n186\t\n187\t## 13. Helfgott-Thompson Does Not Transfer to pi(x) (CONFIRMED numerically, Session 11)\n188\t\n189\t**Statement:** H-T's O(x^{3/5}) method for M(x) = sum mu(n) exploits the signed\n190\tcancellation in (-1)^{omega(n)}. Since pi(x) is a positive counting function\n191\t(1-almost-primes), no analogous cancellation exists.\n192\t\n193\t**Specifics:**\n194\t- pi(x) = pi(z) + A_1(x, z) where A_1 counts primes > z\n195\t- A_1 is irreducible: it IS the prime counting problem\n196\t- The Meissel-Lehmer decomposition pi(x) = Phi - A_0 - A_2 - A_3 - A_4\n197\t  IS the analog of H-T for pi(x), and costs O(x^{2/3})\n198\t- Converting M(x) → pi(x) requires the explicit formula (O(x^{1/2+eps}))\n199\t\n200\t**Source in project:** session11, experiments/sieve/ht_transfer_attempt.py\n201\t\n202\t---\n203\t\n204\t## What Is NOT Proven\n205\t\n206\t- No unconditional lower bound beyond Omega(log x) for pi(x) computation\n207\t- No proof that pi(x) cannot be computed in polylog(x) time\n208\t- PRIMES is not known to be in or outside NC, TC^0, or L\n209\t- **NEW (Session 11):** AKS path to PRIMES in TC^0 requires GROWING-dim (k=polylog(n))\n210\t  matrix powering. Fixed-k MPOW IS in TC^0 (RAIRO 2000). IMP_k (k≥3, different\n211\t  matrices) NOT in TC^0 unless TC^0=NC^1. Growing-dim MPOW is GENUINELY OPEN —\n212\t  sits precisely at the TC^0/NC^1 boundary. Healy-Viola 2006: F_{2^n} exponentiation\n213\t  IS in TC^0 via Frobenius, but doesn't work over Z_n.\n214\t- Circuit complexity of pi(x): all direct TC^0 paths closed (Session 11),\n215\t  but no impossibility proof exists\n216\t- No proof that O(x^{1/2}) is a barrier (only empirical for known methods)\n217\t- Combinatorial pi(x) in O(x^{3/5})? (H-T achieved for M(x) but transfer FAILS)\n218\t"}]},"uuid":"6003bb9d-06f5-4903-969b-4ccd96fd8923","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:38:07.660Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"af430651-6ce3-470c-8cb7-42f3a